##How are the foreigners who didn't leave Wuhan

WECHAT betteryourlife2013

The feature introduces better your life, focusing on the better you and the better world that comes with it.

Let's have more fun in Wuhan! Please click on the top better â†’ click on the upper right corner"..."â†’"set as star"

19,000, according to a July 2018 survey by the Hubei Provincial People's Association, 81 percent of the resident foreigners in Hubei Province are in Wuhan. They frequent Chuhehan Street, Guanggu pedestrian street, Garden Road, Wuda around, Dun Kou, relying on not fluent Chinese and learned a few words of Wuhan, and the people on this land into one.

After the outbreak, the United States, Japan, Australia, Germany, France, the United Kingdom, Sri Lanka, Thailand and other countries announced the evacuation of their citizens from Wuhan, but many foreigners still chose to stay in Wuhan, a brief "dark moment" with Wuhan.

"I love Wuhan because it's a vibrant city. Now the streets are empty and there's no noise, which makes me feel sad, " said Fred, who has lived in Wuhan for nearly 10 years.

How are the foreigners left in Wuhan?

Jake is one of the foreigners in Wuhan, and a special one as well. He was once named "the most fun-eating foreign boss in Wuhan" , the "little praise Wuhan" created by the company provides foreigners in Wuhan with a series of information about eating, drinking and playing, and helps them build a social platform. In Wuhan, 80-90% of foreigners are fans of Xiaozan Wuhan.

Xan, Wuhan's Wechat APP

On Dec. 31, Jake heard about the new coronavirus from a friend, and like most people, he didn't realize the seriousness of the situation, thinking that the virus could only be transmitted directly through a virus source or food. He believed the news reports. There was no basis for human-to-human transmission at the time.

It wasn't until later, when news of the infection spread from the hospital and confirmed cases began to appear abroad, and the number of confirmed cases in Wuhan remained stable, that Jake began to worry about the severity of the outbreak.

On January 13th, at the award ceremony in Xiaozan Wuhan, Jake began having a low grade fever that lasted for about three days before falling. Then he began coughing, sneezing, runny nose and sinus infections. Within days, he began to develop muscle soreness and chest and lung pain.

Jake is celebrating the Wuhan Awards

He could not confirm whether the physical symptoms were caused by the new coronavirus, and was more concerned about being re-infected in the now overcrowded hospital environment. On the advice of his mother, who has a master's degree in nursing, he isolated himself and tried self-medication. Thankfully, things seem to be getting better.

During the interview, Jake frequently used words like "worry, " "nervous, " "afraid, " "concerns, " and his unease was felt across the screen.

"I'm not sure about my condition. But I have a strong feeling that I'm one of the hundreds of new undiagnosed patients. "

January 29, the United States from Wuhan Evacuation Charter plane took off from Wuhan Tianhe Airport, arrived in Alaska and then flew to southern California, landing at Riverside County Air Force Base.

Jake didn't get on the plane because he couldn't prove his health, but he went to the airport on the same day to pick up his best friend and daughter who had been evacuated.

Jake, take a friend to the airport

Asked if he was worried about cross contamination, Jake told me that 99 percent of foreigners in Wuhan did not have their own cars and that the evacuation organized by the consulate did not provide them with transportation to the airport. So he took as many precautions as he could and sent them to the airport.

He had just picked up the mother and daughter from Guanggu at 2:00 p.m. the day before, but at 2:30 a.m. he learned that the girl did not have her passport on her, so he was refused to board the plane, and he had to rush to the airport to pick them up and take them back to Guanggu, didn't get home till 5:00 in the morning.

He remained on standby for the interview and was needed to drive several Britons to the airport once the flight time was set.

In the midst of his anxiety and panic, Jake is already trying to adjust his mind to find a better place. He took his first stab at Chinese food, which, though it took him longer than Western food, gave him peace.

Jake's tiger skin peppers

When the epidemic is over, Jake wants to meet his mother, perhaps try cooking her some Chinese food with his new skills, and tell her how much he loves her.

The Frenchman, Fred, lives near Lihuangpi road in Hankou, one of the worst affected areas.

Fred

This is Fred's tenth year in Wuhan.

He and his wife met at a party. Fred, who is a romantic and art lover, fell in love with Vicky, a wuhan-born music composer. They fell in love at first sight. Together they founded Fufu, a clothing brand, and opened a small shop on Luojiashan Street, Luhuangpi Road, Li Huang, oFFER COFFEE DESSERTS and sell clothes designed by you and your sole agent in France.

Fred and his wife Vicky

Fufu Store on Lai Wong Po road

Around January 15th, Fred got a glimpse of the extent of the epidemic, handing out masks to shop assistants and urging them to clean and sanitize. On January 20, Fred closed the store and temporarily closed it as the epidemic spread further.

On the morning of February 1, the French consulate organized the evacuation of more than 200 people from Wuhan. They informed Fred, but he chose to stay in Wuhan.

After living in Wuhan for nearly a decade, Fred felt like a native of Wuhan. So he decided to stay and sail through the storm with the ship that took him on a long voyage to discover the new world.

Every day, Fred still donned a mask, gloves and glasses, hopped on his bike and cycled from studio to home, finishing his designs, but in the meantime, he had no contact with anyone.

Fred at work

After the outbreak, Fred often felt lonely. Frustrated by the isolation of one million people living in the same city, he longed to meet people and even dance with them on the streets of Wuhan.

Luckily, he had his wife and one-year-old son by his side. These days at home, he has more time to play with his children, Cook some French food and enjoy a cup of coffee in the afternoon.

There was panic in France, says Fred, and the government even set up a hotline to help people answer questions about the new coronavirus. Some people would ask funny questions like, can I get infected if I eat Chinese food? I received the parcel from China. Can I open it safely?

Instead, in Wuhan, he was calmer: "The Chinese government has made all the best decisions for this, and I am confident. "

Roger, an American who first came to Wuhan in 1994, worked at Budweiser's Wuhan Brewery, managing international projects, including the brewery, and made annual business trips to China.

Roger made a lot of friends in Wuhan, which made him feel relaxed. After retiring in 2008, Roger moved to Wuhan and began his China and Asia Tours.

Roger

So far, 201 people have been evacuated from Wuhan, and there are an estimated 1,000 Americans in Wuhan -- As many as a few hundred still remain.

On January 19th, three days after Roger and his wife returned from a holiday in America, the city of Wuhan was closed. Roger's wife was worried about her parents and didn't want to leave Wuhan. In order to make her feel at ease, Roger chose to stay in Wuhan and accompany her.

After the city was closed, Roger took photos of Wuhan

Roger loves the Spring Festival. Since he married his Chinese wife, they have dinner together at her parents'home every New Year's eve and travel to China or other parts of Asia with her after the Spring Festival.

This year they still visited their wife's parents on New Year's Eve, but plans for a post-spring festival trip to Vietnam had to be scrapped. They never went out except to buy needed food and visit their wife's parents. Roger says he's afraid of people.

Ready to go, Roger

While at home, Roger spent his days reading, exercising, watching the news and old TV shows. He was nervous, but generally optimistic.

"The virus will definitely be defeated, and when the epidemic is over, I want to get out of Wuhan for a while, maybe go hiking or skiing in Colorado. "

Takashi Shimada, 72, also stayed in Wuhan.

In 2010, he came to Wuhan and opened a "rooftop curry" in the Chinese teacher Culture Street, which is well known among students. After the demolition of Huashi Culture Street, the rooftop curry was opened at the street entrance and the East Lake village in Hsintien.

Takashi Shimada

Shimada's perception of the outbreak is not strong, he does not understand Chinese, nor online, for the outbreak of all the information from the roof of the store leader of the son. But Dan son afraid of Shimada worry, and did not reveal too much, just tell him notes, let him try not to go out.

Shimada was interviewed by several media outlets in the early days of the outbreak, and after Jan. 23, Shimada declined to follow up with the Japanese media because of confusion about the complexity of the new coronavirus and in order not to spread rumors and cause panic.

For Shimada, Wuhan is his second home, much like his birthplace in Fukuoka, with a cheerful personality and similar climate, making him feel like a teenager again. In addition to having to go back to Japan to get a visa, Shimada spends the New Year at the family's home. After the outbreak, Shimada did not return to Japan thinking: "Wuhan is also my hometown, there is no need to return to Japan. "

Fukuoka, Japan

In these days in Wuhan, Shimada lives the same life as usual, he still reads and writes every day, will also pick vegetables together with everyone. He was happy to have good home-cooked food every day.

Shimada was with the others on the farm

After the outbreak of the roof curry temporarily closed, but because usually do a good job of hygiene, Tachiko is also learning disinfection, Shimada is not too worried about the roof after the situation. For Wuhan, for the sudden outbreak, Shimada is very optimistic.

"everyone in Wuhan is working very hard, and I'm sure it will get better. Go Wuhan. "

While evacuations are underway, there are still large numbers of foreigners in Wuhan, and Fred told me that most of his friends in Wuhan have decided to stay.

For a moment, these foreigners, from different countries and with different faces, were waiting in the city's closed doors, with more than nine million people in Wuhan, for Rescue Dawn after the epidemic.
